  "local_port": 47258,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the procedure to apply to an RTI?",
  "response": "The procedure to apply for an RTI (Right to Information) in India involves several steps:\n\n1. **Identify the Public Authority**: Determine the public authority (government department or institution) that holds the information you need.\n\n2. **Draft the Application**: Write your RTI application clearly and precisely. You can write it in English, Hindi, or the official language of the state. Include the following:\n   - Your name and contact details.\n   - The information you seek, specifying the details as accurately as possible.\n   - The period for which the information is sought (if applicable).\n\n3. **Address the Application**: Address your application to the Public Information Officer (PIO) of the relevant public authority.\n\n4. **Pay the Application Fee**: The fee is usually Rs. 10. It can be paid through different modes such as:\n   - Cash\n   - Demand Draft\n   - Banker\u2019s cheque\n   - Indian Postal Order (IPO)\n   - Some states may have their own specific modes of payment.\n\n5. **Submit the Application**: You can submit the application in various ways:\n   - In person, by visiting the office of the concerned public authority.\n   - By post, sending it to the PIO of the concerned public authority.\n   \n6. **Keep Proof of Submission**: If submitting in person, get a receipt acknowledgment. If sending by post, keep the postal receipt.\n\n7. **Wait for the Response**: The PIO should respond within 30 days. Information related to life and liberty of a person is to be provided within 48 hours.\n\n8. **Receive Information**: The public authority may provide the information, deny the request citing exemptions under the RTI Act, or inform you if the information is not available.\n\n**Additional Steps if Information is Denied or Not Satisfactory:**\n1. **First Appeal**: If you do not receive the information or are not satisfied with the response, you can file a first appeal with the First Appellate Authority (FAA) within 30 days of the response or from when the response was due.\n\n2. **Second Appeal**: If still dissatisfied, you can file a second appeal with the Central Information Commission or State Information Commission within 90 days of the decision from the first appeal.\n\nDocumentation and procedures might vary slightly depending on the state and specific public authority, so it is advised to check the specific details applicable to the public authority you are dealing with.",
